<item>
<title><![CDATA[Why Customer Research Should Come First]]></title>
<link>https://example.com/?p=102</link>
<pubDate>Tue, 27 Jan 2026 09:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
<guid isPermaLink="false">https://example.com/?p=102</guid>
<description></description>
<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>It is tempting to skip research and jump straight to building. We get it, research feels slow when everyone is eager to ship. But the most expensive mistakes we see all share the same root cause: a confident assumption about customers that was never tested.</p>

<h2>Talk to people before you talk to designers</h2>
<p>A handful of honest conversations with real customers will reshape a project more than any internal brainstorm. We listen for the problems people actually have, not the features they think they want.</p>

<h2>Research is a habit, not a phase</h2>
<p>The teams that win treat research as something they do continuously, woven into every release. Small, frequent learning beats one big study that gathers dust on a shared drive.</p>

<p>Start small, stay curious, and let what you hear change your mind. That is where the best products come from.</p>]]></content:encoded>
<excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[The most expensive mistakes all share the same root cause: a confident assumption about customers that was never tested.]]></excerpt:encoded>
