<item>
<title><![CDATA[Choosing the Right Tech Stack for Growth]]></title>
<link>https://example.com/?p=103</link>
<pubDate>Wed, 11 Feb 2026 09:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
<guid isPermaLink="false">https://example.com/?p=103</guid>
<description></description>
<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>There is no perfect tech stack, only the right one for where your business is heading. The shiniest tools are rarely the answer, and the cheapest ones often cost the most over time.</p>

<h2>Optimise for change, not perfection</h2>
<p>Early-stage teams need to move fast and stay flexible. We favour boring, well-supported technology that your team can hire for and that will not box you in two years from now.</p>

<h2>Buy what is undifferentiated, build what sets you apart</h2>
<p>Payments, email, analytics, authentication, buy these. Save your engineering energy for the parts of the product that genuinely make you different. That single principle prevents a surprising amount of wasted effort.</p>

<p>Choose deliberately, document your reasoning, and revisit it as you grow. A good stack quietly gets out of the way so the team can focus on customers.</p>]]></content:encoded>
<excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[There is no perfect tech stack, only the right one for where your business is heading.]]></excerpt:encoded>
