<item>
<title><![CDATA[Leading Change in a Hybrid Team]]></title>
<link>https://example.com/?p=106</link>
<pubDate>Tue, 31 Mar 2026 09:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
<dc:creator><![CDATA[admin]]></dc:creator>
<guid isPermaLink="false">https://example.com/?p=106</guid>
<description></description>
<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>Leading change was never easy. Doing it across a team that is part in the office, part at home, and spread across time zones adds a whole new layer. The old playbook of momentum-by-presence simply does not apply.</p>

<h2>Over-communicate the why</h2>
<p>When people cannot read the room, clarity has to come from words. We coach leaders to repeat the reasoning behind a change far more often than feels natural, in writing, where everyone can find it.</p>

<h2>Make progress visible</h2>
<p>Hybrid teams lose the casual signals that things are moving. Shared, lightweight rituals, a weekly note, a visible roadmap, a quick demo, replace the corridor conversations that used to carry the work forward.</p>

<p>Change still comes down to trust. Build it deliberately, and a distributed team can move just as decisively as one in a single room.</p>]]></content:encoded>
<excerpt:encoded><![CDATA[Leading change across a hybrid team adds a whole new layer. The old playbook of momentum-by-presence does not apply.]]></excerpt:encoded>
